            <fr:title text="Modern ways to teach abstract algebra">Modern ways to teach abstract algebra</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The more modern approaches to teaching abstract algebra incorporates some degree of category theory into the mix.</html:p>
            <html:p>Aluffi's <fr:link href="/aluffi-2009-algebra/" title="Algebra: Chapter 0" uri="http://localhost:8000/aluffi-2009-algebra/" display-uri="aluffi-2009-algebra" type="local">Algebra: Chapter 0</fr:link> is perhaps the most bold attempt to reorganize abstract algebra around category theory entirely. Instead of ending at Galois theory, Aluffi concludes with homological algebra.</html:p>
            <html:p>Some ideas from the traditional approach (like "groups with operators") turn out to be confused and muddled (which should be replaced with groups acting on other groups).</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
